-- tMythen-Bricolage in Film und Theater Frankreichs – das Beispiel Jean Cocteau -- tRevolte gegen das Absurde: Sisyphos nach Camus -- tAus dem Reich der Toten. Korrekturen der Nekyia von Hans Erich Nossack und Arno Schmidt -- tÖdipus in Österreich. Mythische Motive und mythisches Erzählen in Heimito von Doderers Ein Mord den jeder begeht und Ingeborg Bachmanns Ein Wildermuth -- tDürrenmatt in Delphi. Korrekturen des Ödipus-Mythos im Sterben der Pythia -- tEntzauberung – Wiederverzauberung. Die Maschine Mythos im 20. Jahrhundert -- tElektra vor dem Palast. Elfriede Jelinek und die Atriden -- tZerstörung, Rettung des Mythos im Trivialen. Über die Travestie der Tradition in Literatur und Film, in Fernsehen und Comic -- tBiobibliographische Hinweise -- tAbbildungsnachweise -- tRegister der Autoren, Werke, biblischen und mythologischen Figuren0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDer Begriff ‚Mythenkorrektur‘ bezeichnet ein literarisches Verfahren, das den Mythos nicht fortschreibt, sondern überraschende Eingriffe an seinem eigentlich geschützten Kern vornimmt: Schweigende Sirenen oder ein glücklicher Sisyphos. Form und Gestaltungen solcher Korrekturen untersucht der vorliegende Band erstmals systematisch an Beispielen von der Antike bis zur Literatur der Gegenwart.  aThe concept of corrected myths is not (yet) established in literary studies. This volume introduces this concept and demonstrates its power using exemplary interpretations. It is the case that in numerous literary works, knowledge of a conventional mythical connection is assumed, but then, at a particular point, the traditional narrative is negated – Candaule’s wife was not beautiful, the Sirens did not sing, Oedipus was not surprised by the news (Brecht) etc. The corrections always occur at a significant point, so that the intervention casts a new light on well-known narratives, but in principle does not affect the core of the myth. The present volume examines the forms and functions of such corrected myths. For this, relevant works of European literature are studied and their interpretation related with considerations of Antique myths, Christian corrections of myths, new mythology and the correction of myths from existentialism to post-modernism. The spectrum of texts examined is kept as wide as possible to allow for a broad conception of correction. The texts include those from authors such as Heiner Müller, Thomas Brasch, Christa Wolf und Volker Braun and by Shakespeare, Goethe and Kleist.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxClassical influences. 0aMythology, Classical, in literature. 4aAntikenrezeption /i.d. Literatur. 4aEuropa /Literatur, Literaturgeschichte. 4aMythologie /i.d. Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAurnhammer, Achim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennholdt-Thomsen, Anke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirkenhauer, Theresia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDangel-Pelloquin, Elsbeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDehrmann, Mark-Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhlers, Widu-Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmerich, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFebel, Gisela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreiner, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonold, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula